            <pb n="597" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>HUMBOLDT AND THE AMERICANS.<lb break="yes"/>(From the Globe, July 29)</head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Baron</hi> von Humboldt has caused the follow-<lb break="no"
                    />ing article to be inserted in the Berlin <hi rendition="#i">Spen-<lb
                            break="no"/>ersche Zeitung:</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>Under the title of &#x201C;Essai Politique sur l&#x2019;Isle<lb break="yes"/>de
                    Cuba,&#x201D; published in Paris in 1826, I collec-<lb break="no"/>ted together
                    all that the large edition of my<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;Voyage aux Regions
                    Equinoxiales du Nou-<lb break="no"/>veau Continent&#x201D; contained upon the
                    state of<lb break="yes"/>agriculture and slavery in the Antilles. There<lb
                        break="yes"/>appeared at the same time an English and a<lb break="yes"
                    />Spanish translation of this work, the latter en-<lb break="no"/>titled
                    &#x201C;Ensayo Politico sobre la Isla de Cuba,&#x201D;<lb break="yes"/>neither
                    of which omitted any of the frank and<lb break="yes"/>open remarks which
                    feelings of humanity had<lb break="yes"/>inspired. But there appears just now,
                        strange-<lb break="no"/>ly enough, translated from the Spanish transla-<lb
                        break="no"/>tion, and not from the French original, and pub-<lb break="no"
                    />lished by Derby and Jackson in New York, an<lb break="yes"/>octavo volume of
                    400 pages, under the title of<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;The Island of
                    Cuba,&#x201D; by Alexander Hum-<lb break="no"/>boldt; with notes and a
                    preliminary essay, by<lb break="yes"/>J. S. Thrasher. The translator, who has
                        lived<lb break="yes"/>a long time on that beautiful island, has en-<lb
                        break="no"/>riched my work by more recent data on the<lb break="yes"
                    />subject of the numerical standing of the popu-<lb break="no"/>lation, of the
                    cultivation of the soil, and the state<lb break="yes"/>of trade, and, generally
                    speaking, exhibited a<lb break="yes"/>charitable moderation in his discussion of
                        con-<lb break="no"/>flicting opinions. I owe it however, to a moral<lb
                        break="yes"/>feeling, that is now as lively in me as it was in<lb
                        break="yes"/>1826, publicly to complain that in a work which<lb break="yes"
                    />bears my name the entire seventh chapter of the<lb break="yes"/>Spanish
                    translation, with which my <hi rendition="#i">essai <choice><sic>politi-<lb
                                    break="no"/>gue</sic><corr type="editorial">politi-<lb
                                    break="no"/>que</corr></choice></hi>ended, has been arbitrarily
                    omitted. To<lb break="yes"/>this very portion of my work I attach greater<lb
                        break="yes"/>importance than to any astronomical observa-<lb break="no"
                    />tions, experiments of magnetic intensity, or<lb break="yes"/>statistical
                    statements. &#x201C;J&#x2019;ai examiné avec<lb break="yes"/>franchise (I here
                    repeat the words which<lb break="yes"/>I used 30 years ago) ce qui concerne
                        l&#x2019;organisa-<lb break="no"/>tion des sociétés humaines dans les
                        colonies,<lb break="yes"/>l&#x2019;inégale répartition des droits et des
                        jouissan-<lb break="no"/>ces de la vie, les dangers menacants que la<lb
                        break="yes"/>sagesse des législateurs et la modération des<lb break="yes"
                    />hommes libres peuvent éloigner, quelle que<lb break="yes"/>soit la forme des
                    gonvernments. Il appartient<lb break="yes"/>au voyageur qui a vu de près ce qui
                        tourmente<lb break="yes"/>et dégrade la nature
                            <choice><sic>humane</sic><corr type="editorial">humaine</corr></choice>
                    de faire parvenir<lb break="yes"/>les plaintes de l&#x2019;infortune à ceux qui
                    ont le<lb break="yes"/>devoir de les soulager. J&#x2019;ai rappelé dans cet
                        ex-<lb break="no"/>posé combien l&#x2019;ancienne législation
                            <choice><sic>Espagnolle</sic><corr type="editorial"
                        >Espagnole</corr></choice><lb break="yes"/>de l&#x2019;esclavage est moins
                    inhumaine et moins<lb break="yes"/>atroce que celle des Etats à esclaves dans<lb
                        break="yes"/>l&#x2019;Amérique continentale au nord et au sud de<lb
                        break="yes"/>l&#x2019;equateur.&#x201D; A steady advocate as I am for the<lb
                        break="yes"/>most unfettered expression of opinion in speech<lb break="yes"
                    />or in writing, I should never have thought of<lb break="yes"/>complaining if I
                    had been attacked on account<lb break="yes"/>of statements; but I do think I am
                    entitled to<lb break="yes"/>demand that in the free States of the continent<lb
                        break="yes"/>of America people should be allowed to read<lb break="yes"
                    />what has been permitted to circulate from the<lb break="yes"/>first year of
                    its appearance in a Spanish transla-<lb break="no"/>tion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">
                            <hi rendition="#k">Alexander von Humboldt.</hi>
                        </hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rendition="#et">Berlin, July.</hi>
                </dateline>
            </div>
